## Problem

`vendor/waaseyaa/inertia/src/RootTemplateRenderer.php` outputs the initial page object inside this script tag:

```html
<script type="application/json" data-page="true">{"component":"...","props":{...},"url":"/","version":"..."}</script>
```

But Inertia v2's client-side reader (`@inertiajs/vue3` / `@inertiajs/inertia`) looks for the initial page with this selector:

```js
document.querySelector(`script[data-page="${e}"][type="application/json"]`)
// where `e` is the el id, defaulting to "app"
```

i.e. it queries `script[data-page="app"][type="application/json"]`. The literal string `"true"` does not match `"app"`, so the reader returns `null`. Then `createInertiaApp` (`pP` in the minified bundle) does:

```js
const c = s || w0(e, u);  // c is null
const f = d => Promise.resolve(t(d)).then(h => h.default || h);
const S = await Promise.all([f(c.component), ...]);  // null.component
```

Result on every request, in every Inertia consumer of this framework:

```
Uncaught (in promise) TypeError: Cannot read properties of null (reading 'component')
```

The Vue app never mounts. `#app` stays empty. The page renders as a blank document (or whatever non-Inertia content surrounds it).

## Repro

```
git clone https://github.com/waaseyaa/giiken && cd giiken
./bin/waaseyaa migrate && ./bin/waaseyaa giiken:seed:test-community
./bin/waaseyaa serve
# open http://127.0.0.1:8181/ in any real browser
# open devtools → see TypeError, see #app empty
```

Or via headless Chrome:

```
node -e "
const pc = require('puppeteer-core');
(async () => {
  const b = await pc.launch({executablePath:'/usr/bin/google-chrome',headless:'new'});
  const p = await b.newPage();
  p.on('pageerror', e => console.log('ERR:', e.message));
  await p.goto('http://127.0.0.1:8181/', {waitUntil:'networkidle0'});
  console.log('#app len:', await p.evaluate(() => document.getElementById('app').innerHTML.length));
  await b.close();
})();
"
# ERR: Cannot read properties of null (reading 'component')
# #app len: 0
```

## Fix

The renderer needs to emit the data-page attribute with a value matching the el id. The simplest fix is to hardcode `"app"`:

```diff
-        $scriptTag = '<script type="application/json" data-page="true">' . $json . '</script>';
+        $scriptTag = '<script type="application/json" data-page="app">' . $json . '</script>';
```

Better still, accept the el id as a constructor parameter (defaulting to `"app"`) so consumers using a non-default Inertia el id still work:

```php
public function __construct(
    private readonly ?\Closure $template = null,
    private readonly ?ViteAssetManager $assetManager = null,
    private readonly string $appId = 'app',
) {}

// ...
$scriptTag = sprintf(
    '<script type="application/json" data-page="%s">%s</script>',
    htmlspecialchars($this->appId, ENT_QUOTES),
    $json,
);
```

## Workaround

Giiken's `GiikenServiceProvider::registerInertiaViteRenderer` passes a custom `\$template` closure to `RootTemplateRenderer` that runs `str_replace('data-page="true"', 'data-page="app"', \$scriptTag)` on the framework's output before composing the final HTML. Once this issue lands the workaround can be removed. See waaseyaa/giiken commit history.

## Why this hasn't been caught

PHPUnit assertions in the framework only check that the script tag exists and is well-formed; they don't load the page in a real browser. Anything Inertia-related needs to be tested in a real DOM (jsdom, headless Chrome) to catch this kind of contract drift. Suggested companion: a small headless smoke step in CI for the example app.

Related: waaseyaa/giiken#54 (where this was discovered).
